Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Using Histograms(with KDE) and Boxplots for numeric columns

In[]:
# numeric_cols = ['cost_of_the_order', 'food_preparation_time', 'delivery_time']
def drawHistogramAndBoxplot(col):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    # Histogram with KDE
    sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True)
    plt.axvline(df[col].mean(), linestyle='--', label='mean')
    plt.axvline(df[col].median(), linestyle='-', label='median')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(f"{col.replace('_',' ').title()} Distribution")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.show()

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 2))
    # Boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col])
    plt.title(f"{col.replace('_',' ').title()} Boxplot")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.show()

Countplots for categorical columns

In[]:
# cat_cols = ['cuisine_type', 'day_of_the_week', 'rating']
def drawCountPlot(col):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    ax = sns.countplot(data=df, x=col, hue=col, palette='deep', order=df[col].value_counts().index, legend=False)
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(int(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+p.get_width()/2, p.get_height()), ha='center', va='bottom')
    plt.title(f"Order Counts by {col.replace('_',' ').title()}")
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel("Number of Orders")
    plt.show()
In[]:
drawCountPlot('cuisine_type')

American and Japanese food seems to be top ordered cuisines.

Can look at it in two ways.

  1. The top cuisines are higher in demand for existing users. An information that can be used to increase and maintain engagement through partnerships with popular restaurants and marketing the service showcasing top cuisines.
  2. The cuisines with much less order can be seen as a gap or opportunity. There can be additional traffic if the service catered to users with preference to other cuisines

Both information in this case seems very relevant. Depending on the Business goals we can choose either path.

  • Marketing while leveraging currently popular cuisine will be the more common path for accelerating growth. The path is already proven to be effective by current data and exposure to existing customers. This growth path also has some level of assurance for immediate returns.
  • Taking the lack of orders from other less popular cuisines and trying to break into other demographic could be another method for growth but usually this path is taken by services that has reached growth limits with their initial plans since it is associated with higher risk/cost and less immediate return.
In[]:
drawCountPlot('day_of_the_week')

There are more orders on the weekends then on weekdays. Higher foot traffic from Monday through Friday work schedules naturually generate local spending habits. The weekends must be when most people are ordering digitally.

Might be an opportunity to try to advertise for new engagements as well as repeat customers. A good information for marketing.

In[]:
drawCountPlot('rating')

There's quite a lot of "Not given" ratings on the orders. It might be a blindspot if there's too many orders without ratings.

And there's only 5, 4, 3 as ratings. is this due to the limitation in the options? Seems like most people are pretty satisfied when they give ratings.

Increasing engagement with ratings might help us gain more insight.

Top restaurants barplot

In[7]:
def graphTopRestaurants(n):
  top = df['restaurant_name'].value_counts().nlargest(n)
  plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
  sns.barplot(
      x=top.values,
      y=top.index,
      hue=top.index,
      palette='deep'
    )
  plt.title(f"Top {n} Restaurants by Order Count")
  plt.xlabel("Number of Orders")
  plt.ylabel("Restaurant Name")
  plt.show()

# prompt: Show the percent difference between the ratings on weekends and weekdays based on order count

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# Separate orders into weekend and weekday
weekend_orders = df[df['day_of_the_week'] == 'Weekend']
weekday_orders = df[df['day_of_the_week'] == 'Weekday']

# Get the total order count for each
total_weekend_orders = weekend_orders.shape[0]
total_weekday_orders = weekday_orders.shape[0]

# Calculate the percent difference
# Using the weekday count as the baseline for the percentage calculation
# Formula: ((Value on Weekend - Value on Weekday) / Value on Weekday) * 100
if total_weekday_orders > 0:
  percent_difference = ((total_weekend_orders - total_weekday_orders) / total_weekday_orders) * 100
  print(f"Percent difference in order count between weekends and weekdays: {percent_difference:.2f}%")
else:
  print("Cannot calculate percent difference as there are no weekday orders.")

# To also show the distribution of ratings within weekends and weekdays
print("\nRating distribution on Weekends:")
print(weekend_orders['rating'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100)

print("\nRating distribution on Weekdays:")
print(weekday_orders['rating'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100)

# prompt: See if people are ordering more on restaurants with higher ratings. use restaurant_name for uniqueness. Show average ratings breakdown in 0.1 scale. like 4.0... 4.1... 4.2... etc.

# Remove 'Not given' ratings for this analysis
df_rated = df[df['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()

# Convert rating to numeric
df_rated['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df_rated['rating'])

# Group by restaurant name and calculate the mean rating and order count
restaurant_ratings = df_rated.groupby('restaurant_name').agg(
    mean_rating=('rating', 'mean'),
    order_count=('order_id', 'count')
).reset_index()

# Round the mean rating to 0.1 scale
restaurant_ratings['mean_rating_rounded'] = (restaurant_ratings['mean_rating'] * 10).round() / 10

# Group by the rounded rating and sum the order counts
orders_by_rounded_rating = restaurant_ratings.groupby('mean_rating_rounded')['order_count'].sum().reset_index()

print("Average Ratings Breakdown (0.1 scale) and Total Orders:")
print(orders_by_rounded_rating)

# Visualize the relationship
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=restaurant_ratings, x='mean_rating_rounded', y='order_count', alpha=0.6)
plt.title('Order Count vs. Average Restaurant Rating (Rounded to 0.1)')
plt.xlabel('Average Restaurant Rating (0.1 Scale)')
plt.ylabel('Total Number of Orders')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# To specifically show the average orders for each rounded rating bin

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]

In[]:
def compute_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.25
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.15
    else:
        return 0

df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(compute_revenue)
total_revenue = df['revenue'].sum()
print(f"Net revenue generated by the company: ${total_revenue:.2f}")

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]

In[]:
def calculate_total_time(row):
    return row['food_preparation_time'] + row['delivery_time']

df['total_time'] = df.apply(calculate_total_time, axis=1)

orders_over_60_minutes = df[df['total_time'] > 60]

percentage_over_60 = (len(orders_over_60_minutes) / len(df)) * 100

print(f"Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes to deliver: {percentage_over_60:.2f}%")

Conclusion and Recommendations

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]

In[]:
total_orders = len(df)
unrated_orders = (df['rating'] == 'Not given').sum()
pct_unrated = 100 * unrated_orders / total_orders

print(f"Unrated orders: {unrated_orders} of {total_orders}  {pct_unrated:.1f}% didnt leave a star.")

Unrated orders: 736 of 1898  38.8% didnt leave a star.

Conclusions:

  • Cuisine Popularity: American and Japanese cuisines are the most popular, especially on weekends. This suggests a strong demand for comfort food during leisure days.
  • Delivery Time Variation: Delivery times are significantly longer on weekdays compared to weekends. This could be due to factors like traffic, order volume distribution, or driver availability.
  • Restaurant Performance: A few restaurants (Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, Blue Ribbon Sushi, Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken) consistently receive high ratings and have a significant number of orders.
  • Order Cost and Revenue: A substantial portion of orders (around 29%) are over $20, contributing a higher percentage of revenue per order to the company. The orders below $20 may be potential target for revenue growth.
  • Rating Participation: A large number of orders are not rated, which limits the ability to fully understand customer satisfaction across all transactions. 736 of 1898 38.8% are marked 'Not given'.

Recommendations:

  1. Leverage American and Japanese Cuisine: Given the popularity of American and Japanese cuisines, especially on weekends, FoodHub could consider running targeted marketing campaigns or special offers for American and Japanese restaurants during weekends to capitalize on this demand. Use push notifications to engage repeat customers on weekends.
  2. Optimize Weekday Deliveries: Investigate the reasons behind longer delivery times on weekdays. This could involve analyzing traffic patterns, optimizing delivery routes, incentivizing drivers during peak weekday hours, or exploring dynamic pricing based on estimated delivery times.
  3. Promotional Partnerships: Partner with the top-performing restaurants (those with high order counts and average ratings > 4) for exclusive promotional offers through the app. This can encourage more orders from these popular restaurants and reward their consistent performance. Highlighting these restaurants to users could also boost sales.
  4. Target below $20 orders to increase revenue: suggest additional items on checkout to convince users to increase their order cost to drive revenue growth. It is also a better user experience to tag in more items to an order on a single delivery fee.
  5. Restaurant Recommendations in App: Use both rating and other user order count data to link to power recommendation. We can potentially capture users who are on the app but not end up ordering d
  6. Encourage Ratings: Implement strategies to increase customer rating participation. This could include:
    • Push notifications or in-app prompts to rate orders after delivery.
    • Small incentives for providing ratings (e.g., a small discount on the next order for rating the current one).
    • Making the rating process simple and quick within the app. More ratings provide valuable feedback for both FoodHub and the restaurants.

By focusing on top restaurants and cuisines and high weekend engagments, FoodHub can enhance customer experience, strengthen restaurant partnerships, and ultimately drive business growth.
